article.headline: Northwestern St. 76, Centenary 74
article.story: SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) -- Clifton Lee had 19 points to pace Northwestern State to a 76-74 win Tuesday night over Centenary in a matchup that came down to a three-point shot with 12.2 seconds remaining in the game. Centenary (1-3) looked unbeatable in the opening minutes as two quick lay-ups and a three-pointer from Bryan Baumann staked the Gents to a 7-2 lead. A driving basket by Chris Watson with 9:06 to play in the first half gave Centenary its biggest margin of 12 points at 22-10. Northwestern State (3-1) trailed 30-24 at the half after a late push but continued to stay in the game in large part to a 42-29 rebounding advantage. The Demons grabbed 24 offensive boards and converted those second-chance shots into 24 points. With 1:57 left in the game, Watson put Centenary on top 70-69 and he helped widen the gap to three points on another breakaway. Colby Bargeman then grabbed an offensive rebound for the Demons and made good on the put-back for two of his six points to place Northwestern State within one at 72-71. Another board by Bargeman and an assist to Luke Rogers allowed Northwestern State to take the lead again with 54 seconds left on the clock. Watson drove the lane on the Gents' next possession and made the shot to give Centenary a 74-73 lead with just over 30 seconds to play. Lee missed a jumper for the Demons, but another offensive board gave them a second try and Jermaine Wallace nailed a three-pointer from the corner to seal the win. Watson led all scorers with 32 points, while Baumann and Alexander Starr each added 11 for Centenary. Wallace and Keenan Jones chipped in 15 and 12 points respectively for the Demons.
